title: For Sale:  Vintage 1968 FN T-Series Hi-Power with Ring Hammer
postcontent:
Price reduced.

There's a bit of a story here.  I picked up this pistol surplus on gunbroker.  Typical of these pistols, the finish was badly worn, but no rust or pitting and little signs of much use.  In other words, carried a lot, but used little.  This pistol came with black plastic grips with moderate wear (included).  I've replaced with a wooden set with much less wear. postcontent:

That's them with the 100 post listed under 'private party' when it is obvious they are a 'dealer'. Let them keep all the stuff they creep around and buy just so they can try and over charge decent people. Flag'em
And just a pet peeve: If you sell, buy, or trade firearms learn the difference between a clip and a magazine. A clip (or stripper clip) loads a magazine and a magazine loads a firearm. You can not put a clip in a firearm and discharge the rounds. You can only do it with a magazine. You just sound ignorant when you say "I have a 45 semi-auto with 5 clips for sale" Clips are usually a few cents to a few dollars apiece. Magazines are $30 to $100 apiece ( I know drums are more). I'm sure crap firearms magazines are cheaper (don't shoot them don't know).Like I said just a pet peeve. lol

title: For Sale:  Remington Rolling Block late 1800's
postcontent: . Chinese Contract Remington   , serial number range est. 11000 - 25000, over 14,000 produced starting in late 1884, around serial number 14000 the Lee Arms Co. markings were discontinued and the E. Remington & Sons markings moved to the upper left flat on the receiver, Chinese ideograms stamped on receiver ring. The Chinese defaulted on the contract in mid 1885, Remington resold the rifles after removing the Chinese markings, some rifles were fitted with a bayonet lug on the side of the barrel for a saber bayonet, front and rear sights are of the rolling block pattern. This one does not have a cleaning rod or rear sights and is missing the last barrel ring.  In 100% condition it is worth about $2000. Asking $400 OBO. You should have a gunsmith inspect this rifle before firing. The reciever was nickel plated that is well worn. The rear stock is not original. I am selling it for a friend and he does not want to consider trades. All reasonable offers will be considered. REDACTED Don.

title: For Sale:  Mathews LX "MINT"
postcontent: Mathews LX Solo Cam with string silencers on each end of the string and Mathews roller guard system and its silky smooth, 29 inch draw, and 70 pound draw weight, with Trophy Ridge 5 Pin Sight with sight light, Trophy Ridge Stabilizer Bar, Bodoodle Arrow Rest, Scott Release, Alpine 5 Arrow Quiver, and 5 Beeman ICS Hunter 340 arrows that have never been shot, and an SKB Hard shell Bow Case! This bow is built to hunt!! I bought this bow in 2005 and it's been in the SKB case since then. I've taken it out and shot it 5 or 6 times but had to put it up after the fourth or fifth shot due to extreme pain back pain. The bow looks brand new with no scratches. It still has the original string on it and it's in perfect condition. I shot it through the chrono in 2005 and it shot 297 fps, and shot it again through the chrono at Gander Mountain where I work and got 282 fps, but that is due to string stretch. If I was to put a new string on it I believe the FPS would go back up in the 290's. THAT'S SMOKING FAST FOR A BOW AS SMOOTH AS THIS ONE!! I know it would make someone a great hunting bow!! This bow is so smooth, quite, and forgiving to shoot. I have included a 6 arrow group I shot at 20 yards with this bow, and it was the first time I picked this bow up in 4 years. I would put this bow up against ANY new Mathews bow on the market today, and if It didn't beat it, It would surely give it a run for its money! As an added BONUS I'm throwing in 22 Beeman 340 ICS Hunter Arrows with Blazer Vanes and 100 grain field tips for target practice!! These arrows are $6 each so 22 arrows X $6 = $132, the SKB case cost over $200 and the Scott Release was $60! To put it in a nutshell for you, I have over $1100 in accessories alone so you are getting the bow for free!! I have way over $1500 in this stuff folks and all of it is in mint condition. You just have to see it to believe it! When I say mint condition I mean brand new condition! Even the accessories are in brand new condition! I take real good care of my stuff! This is a good deal anyway you look at it and it's worth every dime of $600!! This will be my final price on this bow and accessories. A lot of the accessories are not listed in this ad!

title: For Sale:  2006 F150 King Ranch
postcontent:
Selling my 2006 King Ranch F150. It currently has 172,460 miles on it. I purchased this truck in 2009 and am the 2nd owner. The interior is in good condition. Steering wheel and center counsel leather have the most wear. But, this is pretty common with all King Ranchs bc of the unique leather. Someone keyed the hood a few months back. Other than that it has pretty typical exterior scratches and chips for a truck. Small dent in back bumper so back up beeping sensor does not work. New front windshield. Newer tires, brakes, and alternator. Regular oil changes. Truck was used as a daily driver. Never really hauled anything with it or went off road. Comes with tonneau cover (non negotiable) an spray in bed liner. I use the tonneau cover during winters so it is off right now. Not many F150 King Ranchs come on the market for this price. Here is your chance to own on. Great looking truck overall. I love this truck and hate selling it but I need a car not a truck for my new line of work.

Asking price is $14000 obo. Can provide more pictures.

title: For Sale:  Engraved 1861 Colt Navy Presentation Revolver
postcontent: Fully Engraved 1861 Colt Navy presentation Revolver 36 caliber, very early serial number 9765. I am selling this gun on consignment. It is out of an old Indian Trading Post from Gallup, New Mexico where it has been stored in a vault for over 25 years. This gun is in superb (museum quality) condition. The gun is silver plated and fully engraved by Gustave Young who was Colt's premier engraver from the 1850s through the 1870s. He is often referred to as the Picasso of engravers. His "signature" mark is the dog/wolf head show here in photo #24. The gun's grips are ivory and it has all matching serial numbers. This gun was obviously a custom order gun made as a presentation piece. The back of the back strap was left blank where a persons name would have been engraved (see photo #29). I have been told the Confederacy ordered a small number of these Navy models at the beginning of the civil war to be used as presentation pieces. Because the serial number fits in that same time period it has been suggested that this could very well be one of those pieces? While we know very little about the history of this gun we do know it is extremely rare to find a silver plated Gustave Young engraved presentation gun for sale in this kind of condition. The gun is being offered with an on site inspection and approval by the buyer. It can be shipped registered mail but only after the buyers inspection, approval and payment has been made. Colorado buyers pay state sales tax. Email me with any questions. **************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************** All reasonable offers considered.

postcontent:
So I have a high standard 22lr e Hartford conn here is some info 

Serial number SH20028

This pistol was made late in 1981, .the barrel is off an ISU Olympic model, and that's were i'm assuming they got the grips.....the ISU's had aluminum slides and were often prone to wear, so it wasn't uncommon for people to swap out the match barrels to more sturdy models since the barrel assembly comes off with either a push button on more expensive models, or in this pistols case, the allen screw on the front of the trigger guard. even pieced together the barrel and grips are worth $400 on there own, 500 is a steal  if u know these guns u would agree if u want to run the serial number it's SH20028 
you have to be careful when pricing High Standard pistols, with literly hundreds of different models to choose from only way to get a accurate price is running the serial number which I did
these pistols were built strictly for Bullseye and Olympic style target shooting, and were the standard before all the free pistols started to trickle in. MANY Olympic shooters still use them to this day it has 1 scratch that's noticeable ( see pic) blueing is in good shape and it shoots amazing its insanly accurate $$$650  text or email only REDACTED
